As buyers are building assortment, they work with vendors to finalize the cost and negotiate where they want to position the retail pricing to hit the margin target considering the competitive market place.

Margin = actual price - cost

Every Monday, they review the sales performance (Flow sheet - MTD, STD sales) and for slow items they make pricing decisions. WOS is a key metric to check especially for seasonals. They also consider seasonality builds on the forecast.

WOS = Snapshot of Sunday OH Inventory / Actual Avg. Demand for the last 3 weeks.

There is a promotional calendar collaboratively agreed upon by Marketing, Finance and Merchant teams.

It‚Äôs generally defined a quarter ahead. As the quarter progresses, they can revise the promotions.

Some brands are on MAP and vendors restrict promos. When there is a MAP holiday break, they need to take into account how they‚Äôll execute the promotions. (i.e. $10 off below white tag)

Most products have 12 or 15-month life cycles. Life cycles are defined like 5/7, 7/5, 9/6, 11/4. For example 7/5 means that the product has 7 months to sell regularly and has 5 months to clear before end of life. (Refer to Product Life & Exit Date Calendar)

After they make pricing decisions, they roll-up each office and check the budget with finance in terms of total gross margin impact. (in terms of basis points) They upload on Tuesdays and the stores implement on Thursdays.

They have a promo recap sheet summarizing the promo pairs, dot (mark-down) pairs and white pairs (any cost adj. or wrong price correction) pricing impact on total gross margin. Margin impact can be positive as well. For example they take the prices up before BOGO promotion starts.

They have a Markdown Recap sheet. They review product lifecycles set by the classification by exit date. They have a pricing set using store clusters with $5 increments. Prices ending with .98 reflects the product is on clearance.

They review markdowns weekly on Mondays. They review the sell-thru during last 3 weeks, historical year season, key event, cluster level history to project what it will sell until exit date. They check the projected overhang ( inventory left at exit date)

## Client Summary

noteCompany Name: CaleresSector:Footwear Retailer

Brands:100+ active brands

Revenue: ~$2 Billion (2023)

Product Count: ~10.000 options

Key Products:

1. Footwear
2. Accessories (Mainly socks and backpacks)

Headquarters:St. Louis, Missouri, USA

Global Reach:Operations in the United States ~ 800+ stores

Project Scope:

- Regions In Scope: United States
- Store Scope: Famous Footwear banner
- Out-of-Store Scope: None

Solutions:Pricing and Promotion Optimization, Markdown Optimization

Famous Footwear employs two pricing modules:

1. Promotional Pricing (Item Level) ‚Äì Applied at the beginning of the product's lifecycle to attract customers with dynamic pricing, usually ending in .99.
2. Markdown & Clearance Pricing (Cluster Level) ‚Äì Used when demand slows down, with discounts applied based on demand exit dates and inventory levels.

Used when demand slows down, with discounts applied based on demand exit dates and inventory levels.

- Markdown prices always end in .98, making in-store price adjustments more structured through stickers.
- New markdown rule: If a product's discount exceeds 65%, it is categorized as "early dot", prioritizing its clearance.
- Pricing decisions are based on predefined price bands, using a step-based approach where price changes are calculated relative to ST% targets.

#### 3Ô∏è‚É£ Store vs. Online Pricing Differences

price changes are calculated relative to ST% targets.

#### 3Ô∏è‚É£ Store vs. Online Pricing Differences

- In physical stores, markdown pricing is strictly defined through stickers, ensuring consistency.
- Online pricing is more flexible, prioritizing full-price sales whenever possible before markdowns are applied.
- If a product's inventory is over 70% in the warehouse, it is treated as an online product, and its price is determined based on online sales data.
- MAP (Minimum Advertised Price) Restrictions: Some brands, like Birkenstock, prevent online markdowns, so these products stay at full price online while being discounted in stores.

#### 4Ô∏è‚É£ Forecasting & Optimization Process

at full price online while being discounted in stores.

#### 4Ô∏è‚É£ Forecasting & Optimization Process

- Noob is the forecasting tool that generates weekly sales forecasts for each product based on price steps and demand trends.
- When a product first enters markdown, a temporary price increase can be recommended before further markdowns (e.g., a promo price of $49.99 could be set to $52.98 in its first markdown week).
- Dropship items (~1% of inventory) are outside the pricing system since their inventory is unstable. Pricing optimization for these products is currently in the backlog.
- Items without inventory or forecast data are filtered out from the pricing output.
- The front-end approval system for pricing is still under development, so results are currently shared with the client via Excel.

# Introduction

Markdown is the product that used in the clearence items‚Äô pricing decisions. Its goal is to reach Sell Through Target (% of inventory we want to sell at the end of the period) by introducing discounts to items with minimal Markdown Loss (% of discount given to item). In short, we want to sell most products with the smallest discount rates.

Caleres has a calendar that divides items into 3 phases:

Client can change the phases of products, but these phases are applicable for most of the products, and our calculations are based on them.

Between Demand Exit Date and End of Life (will be referred as EOL) dates the regular markdown algorithm works.

mand Exit Date and End of Life (will be referred as EOL) dates the regular markdown algorithm works.

But after EOL is passed for an item, it no longer qualifies for the algorithm, and will be handled seperately in a SQL Stored Procedure. The process can be summarized as until the item inventory ends, keep giving 25% discounts with 4 weeks tenure. We essentially put the items under death sentence here, they will keep getting discounted until the item is cleared or reaches a minimum price value. This method is requested by the client.

In Caleres, we implemented Benchmark Optimization. Benchmark optimization is an heuristic approach, it relies on a set of rules and parameters, and decides discounts according to them. It is a decision tree. See the picture below, and for better explanation, see the link: [Benchmark Algorithm Step Calculator]

e the picture below, and for better explanation, see the link: [Benchmark Algorithm Step Calculator]

In Caleres, we have a much simpler flow. The algorithm is still the same above, but we don‚Äôt incorporate seasonality and special day checks, we directly look at the sellThruProjection. We don‚Äôt incorporate them in this way because we can give those effects by manipulating Sell Thru Target, which is special to Caleres. In normal markdown settings, we expect the SellThru Target is given to us using the UI, but here we are responsible for the sellThru Target calculation.

SellThruProjection is the projected sellThru at the end of N weeks, N is defined by us as a parameter for the algorithm, which is set to 4 in Caleres.

markdown.BenchmarkMarkdownParameters is the table for setting parameters to this algorithm.

Here are the key adjustments made to transform the original demand exit date into the final demand exit date:

## 1. Product Class-Based Logic

- SSN CORE items: Use a dynamically calculated demand exit date based on the current week's key event timing

- Example: A core shoe style gets its demand exit date recalculated each week based on current market conditions

- SEASONAL/FASHION items: Start with the original seasonal demand exit date from the master calendar

- Example: A summer sandal starts with its planned June 30th demand exit date

- Other product classes: No demand exit date is set (marked as null)

- Example: Special category items that don't follow standard demand planning

## 2. Open Purchase Order Impact

- Items with open purchase orders: Demand exit date becomes the earlier of:

- Original planned demand exit date, OR

- Purchase order arrival date + demand lifecycle months

- Example: A shoe with June 30th exit date but PO arriving May 1st + 2 months = July 1st, so June 30th is kept

- Items without open purchase orders: Demand exit date becomes the earlier of:

- Original planned demand exit date, OR

- Last receipt date + demand lifecycle months

- Example: A boot with no open POs, last received March 1st + 3 months = June 1st vs. planned July 15th, so June 1st is used

## 3. Future Seasonal Item Adjustments

- Specific seasonal items in 2025+ with delayed purchase orders: The last receipt date gets updated to the earliest expected arrival date from purchase orders

- Example: A 2025 spring shoe with POs arriving more than 30 days out gets its receipt timing adjusted

## 4. Customer Override Adjustments

- Custom demand exit dates: If a customer has manually specified a demand exit date for specific items, it completely overrides all calculated dates

- Example: Customer manually sets a popular boot's demand exit date to August 15th instead of the calculated July 30th

## Final Result

The final demand exit date represents the most restrictive (earliest) date after considering:

- Product lifecycle rules

- Inventory pipeline timing

- Customer business decisions

- Purchase order logistics

*Example: A seasonal jacket might start with an October 31st exit date, get reduced to September 15th due to late purchase orders, then get overridden to September 30th by customer preference.*
